# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chamorro-people
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chamorro-people/1969-guamanian-unification-with-the-northern-mariana-islands-referendum] A referendum on union with the Northern Mariana Islands was held in Guam on 4 November 1969.
[src:chamorro-people/1969-guamanian-unification-with-the-northern-mariana-islands-referendum] The proposal was rejected by 58% of voters due to fears about an increase in taxation.
[src:chamorro-people/1969-guamanian-unification-with-the-northern-mariana-islands-referendum] Despite the result, a similar referendum was held in the Northern Mariana Islands on 9 November in which 61% of voters supported union with Guam.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:chamorro-people/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] The village is 10 miles (16 km) southwest of Hagåtña, with most of the residents ethnic Chamorros, the indigenous people of Guam.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Some of Agat's most notable sites are Mount Alifan, the Agat Marina, the Spanish Bridge, and War In The Pacific National Historical Park.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] In 1565, the Spanish explorer Miguel López de Legazpi claimed Guam for Spain.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Agat was founded between 1680 and 1684, by the Spanish Governor Don Jose Quiroga, as a military garrison for the purpose of controlling the Chamorro people and converting them to Christianity.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Many of its first citizens were brought from the internal village of Fina which was destroyed while the Spanish pacified the island.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] It was one of six such settlements on Guam in the 18th century.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] During the 1830s, the Spanish Governor, Captain Villalobos, began constructing facilities in Agat planning to make it the island's new capital.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Lack of funds prevented him from completing the project.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] In 1898, Guam was transferred from Spain to the United States following the Spanish–American War.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Naval administration, Agat was incorporated as a township with an American style municipal government.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] During World War II, Japan occupied Guam from 1941 to 1944.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] During the Battle of Guam in 1944, Agat was one of the two landing sites for U.S.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] These sites are now part of the War in the Pacific National Historical Park.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] The old village was destroyed during the invasion.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] After capturing Guam, the U.S. military constructed a new residential community in Agat for Guam residents made homeless by the war south of the original village.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Lou Leon Guerrero signed a bill officially changing the name of the village.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Census Bureau counts it under the Agat census-designated place.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Guam Public School System serves the island.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Marcial Sablan Elementary School and Oceanview Middle School are located in Agat.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Southern High School in Santa Rita serves the village.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Oceanview Middle School was originally Oceanview High School; the campus became a middle school in 1997.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] In regards to the Department of Defense Education Activity (DoDEA), Hågat is in the school attendance zone for McCool Elementary and McCool Middle School, while Guam High School is the island's sole DoDEA high school.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] DoDEA school material describes the DoDEA school bus services going to Hågat as "limited".
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Our Lady of Mount Carmel Catholic School is located in Agat and accommodates students in pre-kindergarten through eighth grade.
[src:chamorro-people/agat-guam] Guam Public Library System operates the Agat Library at 165 Follard Street.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:chamorro-people/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The **Aloha Festivals** are an annual series of free cultural celebrations observed in the state of Hawaii in the United States based on the Makahiki, the beginning of the Native Hawaiian year marked by the sighting of the Pleiades (*Makali'i*).
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] It is the only statewide cultural festival in the nation.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] Highlights include the presentation of the Royal Court, a ho'olaule'a in Waikiki, and the Floral Parade.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] Approximately 30,000 people volunteer to plan, organize, and provide labor for the Aloha Festivals each year.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] Their efforts entertain over 1,000,000 people from throughout the state and visitors from all over the world.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] In the spirit of preserving the Hawaiian culture and heritage, the Aloha Festivals were established in 1946 as **Aloha Week** by former members of the local Junior Chamber of Commerce.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The former manager of the festivals, Goriann Akau, has said, "In 1946, after the war, Hawaiians needed an identity.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] When we started to celebrate our culture, we began to feel proud.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] We have a wonderful culture that had been buried for a number of years.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The festival was celebrated on six of Hawaii's islands, but in 2008 festival organizers decided to hold most events on Oahu due to a lack of funding.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] There was also the chance that the Floral Parade would be cancelled altogether, but it was saved by private donors and funds from the City and County of Honolulu.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] That was caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, a year which had many disruptions.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The court is selected from a pool of applicants, all of whom must be of Hawaiian ancestry and of certain ages.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The festival itself begins with the presentation of the royal court during the opening ceremony.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The ceremony takes place at Helumoa, a section of Waikiki near the Royal Hawaiian Center.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The Floral Parade starts at the intersection of Ala Moana Boulevard and Kamakee st. and goes through Waikiki before finishing at Kapiolani Park.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The parade features p'au riders, marching bands, hula halaus, and that year's Aloha Festival Royal Court.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] The Hoʻolauleʻa is a block party held in Waikiki.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] There is Hawaiian music, hula, and food.
[src:chamorro-people/aloha-festivals] Attendance is typically in the thousands.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The **Chamorro people** (/tʃɑːˈmɔːroʊ, tʃə-/; also **Chamoru**) are the Indigenous people of the Mariana Islands, politically divided between the United States territory of Guam and the encompassing Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands in Micronesia, a commonwealth of the US.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Today, significant Chamorro populations also exist in several US states, including Hawaii, California, Washington, Texas, Tennessee, Oregon, and Nevada, all of which together are designated as Pacific Islander Americans according to the US census.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] According to the 2020 census, about 63,035 people with Chamorro ancestry live in Guam and another 17,163 live in the Northern Marianas.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Among those, 50,420 identified as Chamorro alone (i.e. no other race) in Guam and 12,001 in Northern Marianas.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Precolonial society in the Marianas was based on a caste system, *Chamori* being the name of the ruling, highest caste.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] After Spain annexed and colonized the Marianas, the caste system eventually became extinct under Spanish rule, and all of the Indigenous residents of the archipelago eventually came to be referred to by the Spanish exonym *Chamorro*.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The name *Chamoru* is an endonym derived from the Indigenous orthography of the Spanish exonym.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The digraph *ch* is treated as a single letter, hence both characters are capitalized at the beginning of a sentence or proper noun, much like *ij* in Dutch.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Some people theorize that Spanish definitions of the word *Chamorro* played a role in its being used to refer to the island's Indigenous inhabitants.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Not only is "Chamorro" a Spanish surname; in Spanish it also means "leg of pork", "beardless [wheat]", "bald", "close-cropped", or "shorn/shaven/[hair or wool] cut close to the surface".
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Around 1670, a Catholic missionary reported that men were sporting a style in which their heads were shaven, save for a "finger-length" amount of hair at the crown.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] This hairstyle has often been portrayed in modern-day depictions of early Chamorros, but the first European descriptions of the physical appearance of the Chamorro people in the 1520s and '30s report that both sexes had long black hair, which they wore down to their waists or even further.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Another description, given about 50 years later, reported that the Native people at that time were tying up their hair into one or two topknots.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro institutions on Guam advocate for the spelling *Chamoru*, as reflected in the 2017 Guam Public Law 33-236.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In 2018, the Commission on the Chamoru Language and the Teaching of the History and Culture of the Indigenous People of Guam announced *Chamoru* as the preferred standardized spelling of the language and people, as opposed to the conventional spelling *Chamorro*.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamorro language is included in the Malayo-Polynesian subgroup of the Austronesian family.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Because Guam was colonized by Spain for over 300 years, Chamorro has acquired many loanwords from Spanish.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] An example is how the traditional Chamorro number system was replaced by Spanish numbers.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro is often spoken in many homes, but this is becoming less common.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] However, a resurgence of interest in reviving the language has occurred, and all public schools on both Guam and the Northern Marianas are now required by law to teach the Chamorro language as part of the elementary-, middle-, and high-school curriculum.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] A commonly spoken phrase in Chamorro is *håfa adai*, a greeting which approximates "hello" in English.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamorros are commonly believed to have arrived in the Marianas Islands from the Philippines c.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Recent advanced DNA testing conducted on the remains of ancient Chamorros showed that the lineage of both the Unai and the Latte periods originated during the Holocene Epoch in eastern Indonesia, most likely Sulawesi, with no direct prehistoric connection to the Philippines.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] They were expert seafarers and skilled craftspeople familiar with intricate weaving and detailed pottery-making.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The latte stone, a megalithic rock pillar topped with a hemispherical capstone, was used by early Chamorros as foundation for buildings, and has since been appropriated as a national symbol.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro society was based on what sociologist Lawrence J.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Cunningham termed the "matrilineal avuncuclan", one characteristic of which is that the brother(s) of the female parent plays a more primary paternal role than biological male parent of a child.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Spanish colonial records show that Chamorro farmers planted seeds according to the phases of the moon.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] For example, farmers on Guam often plant tuber crops such as sweet potato and yams at full moon during low tide.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] According to the University of Guam (UOG), *Unibetsedåt Guåhan*, the history of Agriculture on Guam had an outstanding number of farms reported in the year of 1940.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] With a high number of reports in 1975 and a decline in 2007, those involved field crop production, livestock and poultry, fish and agriculture.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Based on the data, market crop sales decreased and a number of agricultural production is unrecognized.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] According to early Chamorro legend, the world was created by a twin brother and sister, Puntan and Fu'uña.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] As he lay dying, Puntan instructed his sister Fu'uña to make his body into the ingredients of the universe.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] She used his eyes to create the Sun and Moon, his eyebrows to make rainbows, and most of the rest of his parts into various features of the Earth.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Once her work was complete, she descended on an island called "Guåhan", and transformed herself into a giant rock.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] This rock split, and from it emerged all human beings.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Some believe that this rock was once located at the site of a church in Agat, while others believe it is the phallic-shaped *Laso de Fua* located in Fouha Bay in Umatac.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Ancient Chamorros engaged in ancestor veneration, but did not practice a formal "religion" in the sense of worshiping deities.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] At least one account by Christoph Carl Fernberger in 1623 holds that human sacrifice was practiced to placate a "great fish".
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] This claim may be related to a Chamorro legend about why the island of Guam is narrow in the middle.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] According to the legend, a gigantic fish was gradually eating away at the island from both sides.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Although the ancient Chamorros supposedly had magical abilities, the huge creature eluded them.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] When the men were unsuccessful in hunting it down, the women used their hair to weave a net, which grew larger as they sang.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The singing enchanted the fish, and lured it into the giant net.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Enraged that Father Diego Luis de San Vitores had baptized his child, a Chamorro man and his friend killed the priest and Filipino catechist Pedro Calungsod in April 1672, dumping their bodies in the ocean.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro society was divided into two main castes, and continued to be so for well over a century after the Spanish first arrived.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] According to historical records provided by Europeans, such as Father Charles Le Gobien, apparent racial differences existed between the subservient *Manachang* caste, and the higher *Chamor[r]i*, the Manachang being described as shorter, darker-skinned, and physically less hardy than the Chamori.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamori caste was further subdivided into the upper-middle class *Achoti*/*Acha'ot* and the highest, the ruling *Matua*/*Matao* class.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Achoti could gain status as Matua, and Matua could be reduced to Achoti, but Manachang were born and died as such and had no recourse to improve their station.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Members of the Manachang and the Chamori were not permitted to intermingle.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] All three classes performed physical labor, but had specifically different duties.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Le Gobien theorized that Chamorro society comprised the geographical convergence of peoples of different ethnic origins.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] This idea may be supportable by the evidence of linguistic characteristics of the Chamorro language and social customs.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Prior to Spanish contact, Chamorro boys and men wore no clothing and went about fully nude at all times.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro girls went nude until around the age of eight to ten, at which point they began to wear a small genital covering made either of bark, one or more leaves, a piece of a turtle shell or in some cases matting.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Both sexes at times wore hats of woven leaves to protect themselves from the sun.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Father Pierre Coomans wrote of the practice among Chamorro women of teeth blackening/dental lacquering (also a widespread custom in ancient Maritime Southeast Asia, Japan, Southeastern China, and parts of Indochina), which they considered beautiful as a distinction apart from animals.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Fernberger wrote in his account of the Chamorros that "penis pins" were employed as a chastity measure for young males, a type of genital piercing similar to those employed by inhabitants of precolonial maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamorro creation story revolves around two celestial siblings named Puntan and Fu'una.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In time, this creation story underwent a series of modifications due to the complications in passing the story along from generation to generation.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In this Chamorro creation story, Puntan and Fu'una create the world with their body parts and souls.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Puntan's various body parts were turned into the land, his chest into the sky, his eyebrows into rainbows, and his eyes into the sun and moon.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Fu’una having the ability to give life, brought the sun, soil, and waters to life, and with a final transformation, she turned into stone and gave birth to the Chamorro people.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Evidence supporting this creation story can be seen through the names of the villages on Guam as they are named after body parts.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Barrigada translates to flank, Tiyan translates to stomach, Hagatna translates to blood and Mongmong translates to a heartbeat.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Taotaomo'na are spirits of ancient Chamorros.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Birak is a broader term that may refer not only to the undead, but also to demons or general elemental types.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Taotaomona essentially translates to "people of early times," referring to the ancestors of the Chamorro peoples.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Taotaomona is a supernatural ancestral spirit that Chamorros and some neighboring islanders from Rota and Saipan believe in.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Taotaomona possess a strength that far exceeds man and has the ability to cause sickness and death to those who offend them.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The appearance of a Taotaomona can vary as they can be a female or male and can take an attractive form or a monstrous form.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] On March 6, 1521, Ferdinand Magellan and his men, after having crossed the Pacific Ocean, had encountered the first "Indios" since leaving South America.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Later Spanish visitors named the inhabitants "Chamurres", derived from a local term for the upper caste; this was then converted to "Chamorros", an old Spanish term for "bald", perhaps in reference to the local habit to shave.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Over the centuries, the Mariana Islands have been occupied by several foreign countries (Spain, Germany, Japan, United States), and present-day Chamorro society is almost entirely multiethnic, with the inhabitants of Luta/Rota being the least so.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamorros are primarily of Austronesian ancestry, but began to significantly interact with Spanish and Filipinos during the Spanish colonial era (1521–1898 AD).
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Primarily since the late 19th century onward, many Chamorros have intermarried with other Pacific Islanders, mainland Americans, Filipinos, Chinese, and Japanese.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] During the Spanish era, the Spaniards focused their efforts on converting the Native people to Catholicism.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Hezel stated that Chamorros caught or reported engaging in pagan "sorcery" were publicly punished.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Through this, they were given Spanish surnames through *Catálogo Alfabético de Apellidos* or Alphabetic Catalog of Surnames.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] During the Spanish–American War, the United States captured Guam on June 21, 1898.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Under the Treaty of Paris, signed on December 10, 1898, Spain ceded Guam to the United States effective April 11, 1899.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Guam is among the 17 nonself-governing territories listed by the United Nations.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Before World War II, five American jurisdictions were in the Pacific Ocean: Guam and Wake Island in Micronesia, American Samoa and Hawaii in Polynesia, and the Philippines in Southeast Asia.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] On December 8, 1941, hours after the attack on Pearl Harbor, Japanese forces from the Marianas launched an invasion of Guam.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorros from the Northern Marianas, who had been under Japanese rule for more than 20 years, were brought to Guam to assist the Japanese administration.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] This, combined with the harsh treatment of Chamorros during the two-and-a-half-year occupation, created a rift that would become the main reason Chamorros rejected the referendum on reunification approved by the Northern Marianas in the 1960s.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] During the occupation, Chamorros were subjected to forced labor, incarceration, torture, and execution.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] American forces recaptured the island on July 21, 1944; Liberation Day commemorates the victory.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] After World War II, the Guam Organic Act of 1950 established Guam as an unincorporated organized territory of the United States, provided for the structure of the island's civilian government, and granted the people U.S. citizenship.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The governor of Guam was federally appointed until 1968 when the Guam Elective Governor Act provided for the office's popular election.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Since Guam is not a U.S. state, U.S. citizens residing in Guam are not allowed to vote for president and their congressional representative is a nonvoting member.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] They do, however, get to vote for party delegates in presidential primaries.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The increasing numbers of Chamorros, especially Chamorro youth, relocating to the U.S. mainland, has complicated both the definition and preservation of Chamorro identity.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] On Guam, a Chamorro rights movement has developed since the United States gained control of the island.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Leaders of the movement seek to return ancestral lands to the Chamorro people, and attain self-determination.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro culture has over the years acquired noticeable influences from Spanish, Mexican, American, Japanese, and Filipino cultures, as well as the presence of fellow Oceanic (mostly Micronesian) groups.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Influence from the German era in the Northern Marianas is most visible in the form of certain given names and family surnames.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The prehistoric concept of *inafa'maolek* ("doing good for each other", often translated as interdependence) is a core value of traditional Chamorro culture.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Respect for one's family, community, and the elderly (*man åmko'*) are major components, although this varies from person to person and family to family.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The American military has a major cultural influence among the Chamorro; enlistment rates are higher in the Marianas than in any other place in the US.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] On Guam, the enlistment rate is around 14 people per 10,000; by contrast, the US state of Montana, which has the highest per capita enlistment, has a rate near half that, with about eight people per 10,000.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Cockfighting and cockfight-related gambling were introduced by the Spanish and have long been a significant pastime in Chamoru culture, especially among men.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] It is still popular among the members of older generations and with Filipino immigrants, who raise roosters for cockfighting purposes; however, mixed martial arts fighting competitions have grown in popularity as spectator sports, particularly among the members of more recent generations.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Large-scale events are held throughout the year on Guam and Saipan, which feature local competitors and guest participants from abroad.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro life has long centered on one's matriarchal clan.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The concept of a "clan" stemming from a common female ancestor is still observed.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Large extended families remain central to life in the Marianas.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Diabetes and heart disease have become increasingly common among the Indigenous population, as well as among non-Indigenous Oceanic people living in the Marianas, particularly the Carolinian Refaluwasch.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Traditional healers called *suruhånu* (or *suruhåna* for women) are still greatly respected for their knowledge of herbal treatments and spirits.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Most Chamorros are Roman Catholic and few in the Marianas still maintain some customs and beliefs from the time before the first European conquests; some residents of the Marianas will still ask permission from ancestral spirits before entering parts of jungles.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamoru dance is accountable for many cultural practices, such as chant, dance, and storytelling.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Across the United States, many states are introduced to a *Guma*, led by Chamorro dance instructors who have been in historical Guam dance groups.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro dance costumes were traditionally woven and crafted.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The women wore traditional *mestizas* dresses and men wore a *sadí* made from cotton or linen.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] A significant dance move is traditionally shaped by a canoe.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Chamorro people practiced the canoe by, galaidé, of the hand movement or using traditional wooden sticks.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] During the ancient times, outrigger canoes were used during the war, fishing, and sailing era.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Chamorro cuisine is influenced by various cultures.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Examples of popular foods of foreign origin include various types of sweet or savory *empanada*, originally introduced by Spain, and *pancit*, a noodle dish from the Philippines.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The Spanish settlement in the 17th century also introduced cattle, leading to dishes like *tinala' katne*.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Archeological evidence from islands in the Marianas reveals that rice was cultivated there since prehistory.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Red rice made with *achoti* is a distinct staple food that strongly identifies Chamorro cuisine among the many dishes of fellow Pacific Island cultures.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] It is commonly served for special events, such as parties (*gupot* or "fiestas"), *nobenas*, and occasions such as a high-school or college graduations.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The condiment *fina'denne'* accompanies most meals.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Fruits such as *lemmai, mangga, niyok*, and*bilimbines*are consumed in various local recipes.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In the Marianas, Korean, Chinese, Japanese, and American cuisine are also commonly available.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Locally distinct foods include *kelaguen*, a dish in which meat is denatured in whole or in part by citric acid rather than heat; *tinaktak*, a meat dish made with coconut milk; and *kå'du fanihi* (flying fox/fruit bat soup).
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Fruit bats and local birds have become scarce in modern times primarily due to the World War II-era introduction of the brown tree snake, which decimated the populations of local birds and threatens the*fanihi* (fruit bat) population, as well.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Illegal hunting of fruit bats also threatens existing populations.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Spam and other canned meats were introduced to the islands after World War II, leading to a dietary shift.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] According to the 2020 census, there are roughly 168,226 Chamorros living in the United States (alone or in combination), of whom 81,287 identify as Chamorro alone (i.e. with no additional racial or ethnic identity).
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The early Chamorros who migrated to the US were Guamanians who moved in the first decade of the 20th century.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In the following decades, small groups of Guamanians emigrated to Hawaii and the Western United States, where they worked as farmers.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] The population of Guam got the American citizenship in 1929.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] During the 1930s the military induction of young Chamoru men into the US Navy led to the first wave of Chamoru military families leaving Guam in the 1940s after WWII.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] So, after the end of World War II, many more Guamanians emigrated to the US.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Most of them were in the military or married with military people.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In 1950, the population of Guam gained the full American citizenship, which favoured Guamanian migration to the US.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] So, the first major Guamanian migration emerged and more of 160 Guamanians emigrated to the US in the '50s.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In 1952, Guamanian immigrants founded their first organization in US, the Guam Territorial Society (later renamed as the Guam Society of America), in Washington, D.C., where many worked for the Department of Defense and developing military operations.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In the 1960s, hundreds of Guamanians migrated to the United States, when the largest numbers emigrated to this country.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] Most of them were fleeing the Korean War and Typhoon Karen.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In the '70s, another wave of Guamanians arrived in the US.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] In 1986, the US acquired the Northern Mariana Islands, which favoured migration from islands to the US.
[src:chamorro-people/chamorro-people] San Diego County, California, has the largest Chamorro population with 9,391 persons or 0.24% of the total population.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:chamorro-people/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:chamorro-people/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
